{{Quote|It's over, Anakin. I have the high ground!|Obi-Wan Kenobi to Darth Vader|<ref name="ROTS">{{Film|III}}</ref>}}
'''Sokan''' was a principle of [[Lightsaber combat/Legends|lightsaber combat]], rather than a true form.
Developed by the ancient [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knights]] during the [[Great Hyperspace War/Legends|Great Hyperspace War]], Sokan teaching revolved around using the environment itself to gain a tactical advantage in combat.<ref name="CSWE">''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref>

==Description==
[[File:Sokan-CotF.png|thumb|250px|right|[[Namman Cha]] uses Sokan to his advantage.]]
Sokan involved maneuvering so that swift strokes of the [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]] could be aimed toward the opponent's vital areas, using quick tumbles, jumps, and movements. Combatants made use of large amounts of terrain, trying to maneuver their opponents into vulnerable areas during the course of battles that involved Sokan techniques. This technique allowed for great speed and mobility and left no openings in one's defense. Prior to the Clone Wars, Sokan practitioners integrated highly kinetic elements of [[Form IV/Legends|Ataru]] with their ancient Sokan techniques to create a blend of styles that relied upon agility. It was recommended for practitioners to use this style in their home ground or on familiar terrain.<ref name="CSWE" />

===Known Moves and Maneuvers===
====High Ground Defense====
Taking advantage of terrain to gain a defensive advantage.<ref name="JATM">''[[Jedi Academy Training Manual]]''</ref>

====Unhindered Charge====
A rapid charge at the opponent, circumventing terrain and obstacles to cover the distance quickly.<ref name="JATM" />

==Applications==
{{Quote|That's it. Come to me. ''[&hellip;]'' You think you're driving me back. You have no idea that I'm in control. You don't know where I'm taking you.|Darth Maul's thoughts as he draws two Jedi into a trap|<ref name="The Wrath of Darth Maul">''[[The Wrath of Darth Maul]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Laser_gates.png|thumb|left|225px|Darth Maul achieves Sokan against his enemies.]]
[[Darth Maul/Legends|Darth Maul]] took an unorthodox method of Sokan as he sought a way to control his [[Battle of Naboo/Legends|incoming duel]] with [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]] and [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]] [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]]. He found his answer in the [[Plasma Refinery Complex]], which housed [[Laser gate/Legends|laser gates]] that could turn for just a few seconds, leading into a narrow melting pit. When the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] arrived, Maul lured them into a place of his choosing, separating Jinn and Kenobi by several platforms. He went on to bait Jinn towards the melting pit, the laser gates keeping Kenobi from coming to his Master's aid.<ref name="End Game">{{StoryCite|story=End Game|book=Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace (novelization)|bformatted=''Star Wars'': Episode I ''The Phantom Menace'' novelization, 2012 edition}}</ref><ref name="TPM">{{Film|I}}</ref> Jinn, while partially realizing what his [[Sith/Legends|Sith]] adversary was up to, nonetheless persisted alone. That proved to be a mistake.<ref name="TPM novel">[[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace (novelization)|''Star Wars'': Episode I ''The Phantom Menace'' novelization]]</ref> Not only was his fighting style, Ataru, taxing on the user,<ref name="JATM" /> but it also required open spaces for maneuverability.<ref name="TFU novel">[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed (novelization)|''Star Wars: The Force Unleashed'' novelization]]</ref> Maul, as a result, killed the elder Jedi and nearly succeeded against Kenobi.<ref name="TPM" />

In his brief duel with [[Dooku/Legends|Darth Tyranus]] during the [[First Battle of Geonosis/Legends|First Battle of Geonosis]], [[Yoda/Legends|Master Yoda]] used a three-point leap around the hangar in which they were fighting to evade Tyranus' bladework and regain the initiative against him.<ref name="ATOC">{{Film|II}}</ref>

Although it was unclear whether Obi-Wan Kenobi received formal Sokan training or not, the Jedi Master did employ elements of Sokan while [[Duel on Mustafar/Legends|dueling]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] on [[Mustafar/Legends|Mustafar]]. Toward the end of the duel, Obi-Wan sought the high ground and used his favorable positioning to defeat Vader, attacking his weak points. This was the factor that led to Vader's defeat. However, the [[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] seemed to have learned his lesson from this defeat and was known to use a [[Telekinesis/Legends#Saber Throw|saber throw]] when his opponents gained the high ground rather than pursue them, like in [[Battle of Endor/Legends#Demise of the Sith|his final duel with his son]].<ref name="ROTS" /><ref name="ROTJ">{{Film|VI}}</ref>

